  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nErigon version: erigon version 2.37.0-dev-ed9b1ca7\r\n\r\nOS & Version: OSX\r\n\r\nCommit hash: ed9b1ca7\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\n`make user_macos` should not fail\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\n```\r\nÂ» make user_macos                                                                                                   \r\nsudo dscl . -create /Users/erigon\r\nsudo dscl . -create /Users/erigon UserShell /bin/bash\r\nsudo dscl . -list /Users UniqueID | grep erigon | grep 3473 || sudo dscl . -create /Users/erigon UniqueID 3473\r\nsudo dscl . -create /Users/erigon PrimaryGroupID 3473\r\nsudo dscl . -create /Users/erigon NFSHomeDirectory /Users/erigon\r\nsudo dscl . -append /Groups/admin GroupMembership erigon\r\nsudo -u erigon mkdir -p ~erigon/.local/share\r\nmkdir: /Users/erigon: Permission denied\r\nmake: *** [user_macos] Error 1\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe dev user has sudo, and previous admin commands succeed. I believe it may be that the failed command is run as `erigon` so does not have permissions to create the directory.\r\n\r\nSubsequently, `docker compose up` components report fatal errors because they cannot create file system artifacts. For example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nerigon-rpcdaemon-1   | Fatal: failed to save node key to /.local/share/erigon/nodekey: mkdir /.local: permission denied\r\nerigon-rpcdaemon-1   | Fatal: failed to save node key to /.local/share/erigon/nodekey: mkdir /.local: permission denied\r\n```\r\n",
